Now, back to the socks,<br><br>
I loved the smell of Nam in the early morning hours, the red earth you could both taste and smell. The beauty of its landscape. The monsoon rains were never despairing to me but enticing, Forrest Gulp left a lot out of the description he gave us about the monsoon rains and what we experienced in Nam.<br><br>
”From Dreams of Glory, Clear Fields of Fire,” © 1997, by Cook Barela, 1997<br><br>
Night Patrol <br>
August, 23, 2997<br><br>
”During the day in Viet Nam you could see the rain coming. Often it would come in from the South China Sea in a Southwest direction, but just as often it came from the An Hoa Mountains in a Northeast direction and you could visibly see the rain creep over the mountains around the sides and into the valley's below. <br>
It was like seeing a large sheet of  blueish-gray colored cellophane being unrolled slowly over the mountains range and being laid over the valley's below. Unlike the rest of Viet Nam the monsoon rains in Quan Nam province came twice a year. It rained fast and slow, down and hard, in soft caressing mists or in terrorizing torrents.  The rain was not only wet, cold and heavy, it also had its own sounds and smells, but it also took on various shapes, intensity and power. <br>
The worst storms we experienced came when the South China Sea winds blew, every which way and there was no where for us to turn away from the rain. <br>
We would be going out about four miles, near the area where G………..ing had gotten wounded, Dumont told us.<br>
Dumont was right about it raining. As we settled up it started to rain. By the time we left the perimeter’s wire we were drenched. While it was still early in the monsoon season we had already experienced some days and nights of constant rain. Pouring wet, miserable and cold monsoon rains. The night before us seemed like it was going to be one of those discomforting nights. <br>
During my tour I would see rain act like I had never seen it behave before. Sometimes it would pour down in torrents, or it would sprinkle at us sideways. At times it came at us from the east, and from the west, from the south and from the north. At times it seemed that it came at us from the four corners of the earth at the same time. <br>
At times we stepped into rice paddy fields and the sucking mud held us in place as rain poured down into our ponchos and flowed like clear sheets over our helmets. The rain water in the paddies sometimes met us ankle deep, at times we were up to our waist or chest level, the difference was made, often by just a few steps in either direction. <br>
I now, understood why the Seabees had built the barracks so high off  the ground. It was a precaution against the monsoon floods. We were now always wet, and only occasionally did we sleep in the barracks. <br><br>
Most of our nights were spent on watch out in the bunkers, or out on night ambushes. Everything became soaked, inside the barracks and in the bunkers where everything was constantly wet and the insides of the bunkers flooded.<br>
Our biggest problem was keeping our feet dry.  They remained swiveled and water logged for days. To help keep our feet dry and free of infections, the Marine Corps had issued us foot powder in little green containers, and we sprinkled the white powdery stuff on our feet and poured it into our socks and over our shoulders for good luck or used it as an after shave cologne to help us smell good.  We were never issued enough socks, but there was always plenty of foot powder, we had small cans and big cans of the stuff, but no socks.”  <br><br>

